WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.000
Korea had no future.

00:02.000 --> 00:04.000
At their current fertility rate right now,

00:04.000 --> 00:08.000
for every 100 Koreans, there will be 5.9 great grandchildren.

00:08.000 --> 00:12.000
We are looking at a 94% population collapse over the next century.

00:14.000 --> 00:17.000
Why have you been in the news so much recently?

00:18.000 --> 00:23.000
Because I am calling out that the emperor has no clothes right now,

00:23.000 --> 00:28.000
and I think a lot of people have mentioned collapsing fertility rates before,

00:28.000 --> 00:34.000
but I think that no one has really so consistently

00:34.000 --> 00:40.000
brought it up in a way that the people who want to ignore it

00:40.000 --> 00:42.000
have to look at the problem.

00:42.000 --> 00:44.000
When I point it out, because I think a lot of people,

00:44.000 --> 00:46.000
especially on the more progressive side of the spectrum,

00:46.000 --> 00:48.000
they just want to dismiss it.

00:48.000 --> 00:50.000
Oh, the planet's better without humans or whatever.

00:50.000 --> 00:55.000
But when you point out that not a single society on Earth today,

00:55.000 --> 00:58.000
except for maybe Israel, we can talk about that later in the conversation,

00:58.000 --> 01:03.000
has figured out how to have prosperity, gender equality,

01:03.000 --> 01:07.000
and high levels of education, and anywhere close to a stable population,

01:07.000 --> 01:11.000
considering we are trying our best, and I think rightfully so,

01:11.000 --> 01:13.000
to spread those things across the world,

01:13.000 --> 01:15.000
that should be like a note.

01:15.000 --> 01:19.000
That should be like, oh, this system that we think is so great

01:19.000 --> 01:23.000
and we want to be the future of human civilization doesn't seem to work

01:23.000 --> 01:26.000
at the most basic level.

01:26.000 --> 01:30.000
That seems like quite a scary proselytization for the future,

01:30.000 --> 01:32.000
or prediction for the future.

01:32.000 --> 01:37.000
If you're to say that we need to get rid of one from education, equality,

01:37.000 --> 01:41.000
prosperity, or birth rate,

01:41.000 --> 01:44.000
we just need to concede the fact that birth rate.

01:44.000 --> 01:48.000
What we need to do is we need to find new cultural solutions.

01:48.000 --> 01:52.000
We need to find a way to maintain fertility rates

01:52.000 --> 01:56.000
while having education, while having gender equality,

01:56.000 --> 01:59.000
and while having a high level of prosperity.

01:59.000 --> 02:02.000
There are many places we can look in the world today

02:02.000 --> 02:05.000
to begin to get inspiration for how we might do that.

02:05.000 --> 02:08.000
I think to understand the scale of the threat right now,

02:08.000 --> 02:12.000
one of the things I always start people with is when I started caring about this.

02:12.000 --> 02:15.000
A lot of people are like, why is it that people in Silicon Valley

02:15.000 --> 02:17.000
seem to care about this so much?

02:17.000 --> 02:19.000
It's because there's a lot of VCs in Silicon Valley,

02:19.000 --> 02:23.000
VCs need to chart the economy 50-100 years in the future

02:23.000 --> 02:25.000
in the way that Wall Street people really don't.

02:25.000 --> 02:28.000
They're looking at the economy 5-10 years out or whatever.

02:28.000 --> 02:30.000
Because of that, when I was working as a VC,

02:30.000 --> 02:33.000
I happened to be working in Korea when I was working in a VC,

02:33.000 --> 02:36.000
and I kept trying to chart the future of the economy,

02:36.000 --> 02:38.000
and I kept coming to the same answer.

02:38.000 --> 02:41.000
Is it Korea had no future?

02:41.000 --> 02:43.000
At their current fertility rate right now,

02:43.000 --> 02:47.000
for every 100 Koreans, there will be 5.9 great-grandchildren.

02:47.000 --> 02:51.000
We are looking at a 94% population collapse over the next century.

02:51.000 --> 02:54.000
When I brought this up with the other partners at my firm,

02:54.000 --> 02:57.000
and I was like, hey, it just doesn't seem like

02:57.000 --> 03:00.000
there is any feasible economic future for this country.

03:00.000 --> 03:03.000
They're like, yeah, but we pretend that's not the case in our investments.

03:03.000 --> 03:06.000
Everybody knows this, but if we accepted it,

03:06.000 --> 03:10.000
then the economy stops working, society stops working.

03:10.000 --> 03:12.000
We're just going to ignore it basically.

03:12.000 --> 03:16.000
When I came back to the US, it was like going back in time 20 years.

03:16.000 --> 03:18.000
I was in some sort of a sci-fi movie,

03:18.000 --> 03:22.000
and getting to be this one person who saw where the future was going to go,

03:22.000 --> 03:25.000
and having to be that crazy person on the streets.

03:25.000 --> 03:27.000
No, no, no, you guys don't understand.

03:27.000 --> 03:30.000
There's countries further ahead than us on this spectrum right now,

03:30.000 --> 03:33.000
and we know a few things. We know there is no floor.

03:33.000 --> 03:36.000
No country has hit a fertility collapse floor yet.

03:36.000 --> 03:40.000
We know that there is no level of advanced fertility collapse where people freak out,

03:40.000 --> 03:43.000
or at least not until it's too late, because you look at Korea right now,

03:43.000 --> 03:47.000
60% of Korean citizens are over the age of 40.

03:47.000 --> 03:52.000
It's likely already too late for them to turn this problem around.

03:52.000 --> 03:55.000
We need to turn this around before we hit that level,

03:55.000 --> 03:57.000
but the truth is we probably won't,

03:57.000 --> 04:01.000
and we've got to think of solutions for when we don't turn this around,

04:01.000 --> 04:03.000
but that's a different topic for later in the interview.

