why should anyone care about how many children another person has?

04:11.000 --> 04:13.000
This is my choice.

04:13.000 --> 04:17.000
You can't impose me to have kids if I don't want to have them.

04:17.000 --> 04:21.000
Why should two guys sat on the Internet be telling the world

04:21.000 --> 04:23.000
about the dangers of not having children?

04:23.000 --> 04:26.000
People can go and do other things with their lives now.

04:26.000 --> 04:28.000
Women are allowed to be in the workplace.

04:28.000 --> 04:31.000
Men can go their own way and play video games

04:31.000 --> 04:34.000
and be a Sigma male as much as they want.

04:34.000 --> 04:37.000
Why should anyone care about how many children another person has?

04:37.000 --> 04:40.000
So I think that that's a really good point.

04:40.000 --> 04:43.000
In our foundation, I think one of the things that people most often get wrong about us

04:43.000 --> 04:46.000
is that we are trying to increase the world's population

04:46.000 --> 04:52.000
or that we are trying to proselytize broadly to increase fertility rates.

04:52.000 --> 04:54.000
And neither one of those things is true.

04:54.000 --> 04:56.000
If we are on the Titanic right now,

04:56.000 --> 04:58.000
no matter what the Titanic hits the iceberg,

04:58.000 --> 05:03.000
we are trying to, one, make people aware that the Titanic is about to hit an iceberg,

05:03.000 --> 05:08.000
get them in lines by the rafts, the ones who want to survive,

05:08.000 --> 05:13.000
start getting the rafts in the water in a common orderly fashion before people start panicking

05:13.000 --> 05:15.000
because that's what's going to happen.

05:15.000 --> 05:19.000
And so what we promote is trying to get,

05:19.000 --> 05:21.000
I mean, I know my family is going to be okay.

05:21.000 --> 05:24.000
You know, I know that my cultural group is going to be okay.

05:24.000 --> 05:27.000
Broadly speaking, so one, I know that my family,

05:27.000 --> 05:29.000
you know, I have eight kids and they have eight kids

05:29.000 --> 05:30.000
and you do that for 11 generations.

05:30.000 --> 05:33.000
That's more descendants than exists in the world today, I often say.

05:33.000 --> 05:35.000
So I don't need to worry about people like me.

05:35.000 --> 05:40.000
The reason I'm so loud about this is because I'm worried about the massive collapse

05:40.000 --> 05:45.000
in cultural and ethnic diversity the world is about to see.

05:45.000 --> 05:49.000
And it will be astonishing for people.

05:49.000 --> 05:54.000
I think in the far future, there were more than like three ethnic groups

05:54.000 --> 05:57.000
and three cultural groups or something like that if we don't solve this.

05:57.000 --> 05:59.000
And so what we're trying to do is just make people aware of this

05:59.000 --> 06:03.000
because so much of the propaganda that people are consuming is telling them,

06:03.000 --> 06:08.000
things are fine, have less kids, you're a good person if you have less kids.

06:08.000 --> 06:12.000
And I know you've talked about this before on the show and it is, it is astonishing.

06:12.000 --> 06:19.000
And I think when we look at this urban monoculture that is erasing all of the genuine diversity in our society,

06:19.000 --> 06:22.000
one of its core messages is negative utilitarianism.

06:22.000 --> 06:27.000
That the core evil thing in the world is human suffering

06:27.000 --> 06:29.000
and that human happiness just doesn't really matter

06:29.000 --> 06:31.000
or it is largely outweighed by human suffering.

06:31.000 --> 06:34.000
And therefore it's better if humans don't exist.

06:34.000 --> 06:36.000
And that's the end goal for the urban monoculture.

06:36.000 --> 06:38.000
I think for a lot of people.

06:38.000 --> 06:40.000
What do you mean when you say urban monoculture?

06:40.000 --> 06:45.000
Well, okay, so this sort of gets down to like my personal politics to some extent.

06:45.000 --> 06:48.000
But I think that if you look at society right now,

06:48.000 --> 06:51.000
it's largely becoming divided into two factions

06:51.000 --> 06:56.000
and there has been a major political shift around what conservative and progressive means.

06:57.000 --> 07:00.000
The progressive is a party of this urban monoculture,

07:00.000 --> 07:06.000
which is a single sort of cultural group or virus that infects other cultural institutions

07:06.000 --> 07:11.000
and erases whatever makes them unique and aligns all of their goals.

07:11.000 --> 07:16.000
So if I talk with a progressive Muslim or a progressive Jew or a progressive Catholic

07:16.000 --> 07:20.000
or a progressive Unitarian Universalist and I scratch beneath the surface,

07:20.000 --> 07:23.000
often their morals, their views on gender,

07:23.000 --> 07:27.000
their views on what future they want for the world are all very, very similar.

07:27.000 --> 07:30.000
If I look at conservatives from each of those factions,

07:30.000 --> 07:32.000
their worldviews are very different.

07:32.000 --> 07:35.000
And what the conservative party seems optimizing around,

07:35.000 --> 07:37.000
so where the liberal party is optimizing on the goals of this monoculture,

07:37.000 --> 07:41.000
so spreading the monoculture and reducing in the moment human suffering,

07:41.000 --> 07:43.000
that's why they promote things like haze,

07:43.000 --> 07:46.000
you know, like don't tell somebody that it's unhealthy to be fat

07:46.000 --> 07:47.000
because that could hurt their feelings in the moment,

07:47.000 --> 07:50.000
even though like obviously it's bad for them in the long term.

07:50.000 --> 07:57.000
But the conservative movements all have very distinct cultural histories

07:57.000 --> 07:59.000
which they are trying to preserve.

07:59.000 --> 08:02.000
And that is often, if I look at the conservative movement today,

08:02.000 --> 08:08.000
it's an alliance of these older traditions and newer but deviant and distinct traditions

08:08.000 --> 08:14.000
that are trying to maintain cultural fidelity and exist 100, 200 years from now.

08:14.000 --> 08:17.000
And so when I talk about the monoculture, that's what I'm talking about.

08:17.000 --> 08:20.000
This thing that wants to, when my kids go to school, say,

08:20.000 --> 08:23.000
this is what correct morality is, this is the way you should see the world.

08:23.000 --> 08:26.000
And if your parents are telling you anything else, they're deplorable and wrong.

08:26.000 --> 08:31.000
Is that not the case with some factions from a conservative side as well, though?

08:31.000 --> 08:34.000
Yeah, yeah, no, and I call them sleeper progressives.

08:34.000 --> 08:38.000
They just want to erase all other cultures the moment they gave power.

08:38.000 --> 08:42.000
But I think that right now I can form an alliance with them because our goals are aligned.

08:42.000 --> 08:45.000
I think one of the really cool things that we've seen with the conservative party

08:45.000 --> 08:48.000
is you saw something like when Andrew Tate converted to Islam.

08:48.000 --> 08:51.000
In the past, a conservative icon converting to Islam,

08:51.000 --> 08:53.000
a lot of people would have been wringing their hands about that,

08:53.000 --> 08:54.000
but a lot of people were like, you go.

08:54.000 --> 08:57.000
At least you found some faith, at least you found some tradition.

08:57.000 --> 09:01.000
And so I think what we're seeing there is more of a realization

09:01.000 --> 09:07.000
that the big bad these days is this culture that's trying to homogenize the world.

09:07.000 --> 09:08.000
Interesting.

09:08.000 --> 09:11.000
What would you say to the well-meaning people from the progressive movement

09:11.000 --> 09:16.000
to say it feels a little bit bad to be tarnished with the brush as a super virus?

09:16.000 --> 09:19.000
