09:47.000 --> 09:52.000
and were burning people at the stake and trying to ensure that everybody fit

09:52.000 --> 09:56.000
this very narrow definition of morality set by their culture,

09:56.000 --> 10:00.000
to me they were the evil ones within those institutions.

10:00.000 --> 10:04.000
And today, when I talk about this monoculture,

10:04.000 --> 10:07.000
I think that the vast majority of people who are members of it

10:07.000 --> 10:11.000
were the vast majority of Catholics and Protestants during periods

10:11.000 --> 10:15.000
when those cultural groups were dominant in specific regions.

10:15.000 --> 10:18.000
Why is this culture so effective?

10:18.000 --> 10:19.000
Very interesting.

10:19.000 --> 10:23.000
Okay, so it's evolved a lot of new tactics that had never been tried before.

10:23.000 --> 10:25.000
So in our book, The Pragmatist Guide to Crafting Religion,

10:25.000 --> 10:28.000
what we essentially do is we argue that humanity can be thought of

10:28.000 --> 10:33.000
as sort of an evolving firmware, which is like our biology, our genes.

10:33.000 --> 10:36.000
But on top of that firmware, there's evolving sets of software.

10:36.000 --> 10:39.000
And this software, today we often talk about memes

10:39.000 --> 10:42.000
as like things that infect somebody and then cause them to just turn around

10:42.000 --> 10:43.000
and infect other people.

10:43.000 --> 10:47.000
But historically, most romantic clusters actually augmented a person's

10:47.000 --> 10:51.000
sort of biological fitness, the number of surviving offspring they had,

10:51.000 --> 10:52.000
and that's how they survived.

10:52.000 --> 10:55.000
That's how, I mean, if you look at things with a secular mindset,

10:55.000 --> 10:59.000
why things like Islam and Judaism figured out stuff like handwashing

10:59.000 --> 11:03.000
literally centuries before science figured out handwashing.

11:04.000 --> 11:06.000
And you see this across these traditions.

11:06.000 --> 11:08.000
For example, if you look at all of the old traditions,

11:08.000 --> 11:11.000
almost all of them have some arbitrary self-denial holiday,

11:11.000 --> 11:15.000
like Lent or Ramadan or Feast of the First Burner, whatever, right?

11:15.000 --> 11:19.000
And just now, after throwing out all of those rituals over the past,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
you know, 50, 100 years, secular society is like,

11:22.000 --> 11:24.000
oh, now we got to have our juice cleanses.

11:24.000 --> 11:27.000
Now we got to have our, you know, they're realizing of fasting

11:27.000 --> 11:28.000
and stuff like that, right?

11:28.000 --> 11:30.000
It has positive mental effects.

11:30.000 --> 11:33.000
And so I think that if you see these as different,

11:33.000 --> 11:35.000
like evolving cultural groups,

11:35.000 --> 11:40.000
this super virus evolved some very unique tactics,

11:40.000 --> 11:43.000
and it is not the same thing as a historic progressive movement.

11:43.000 --> 11:46.000
What it is is something, so the reason I call it a super virus is

11:46.000 --> 11:49.000
that it is very much so when you talk about a super bacteria

11:49.000 --> 11:52.000
or a super bug, they typically come up in things like hospitals

11:52.000 --> 11:55.000
where you have a ton of people with a weakened immune system

11:55.000 --> 11:59.000
all in a similar environment with lots of sort of viruses or bacteria

11:59.000 --> 12:03.000
that can intermingle alongside antibiotics and stuff like that.

12:03.000 --> 12:05.000
This is what was created by the internet.

12:05.000 --> 12:09.000
This is why all of this stuff started when social media happened.

12:09.000 --> 12:16.000
Essentially, you had a super spreader environment where pneumatic ideas

12:16.000 --> 12:20.000
were able to test themselves against all of the world's traditions

12:20.000 --> 12:23.000
at the same time, optimize and react very quickly

12:23.000 --> 12:29.000
and become incredibly virulent while evolving strategies

12:29.000 --> 12:31.000
that had never been tried before.

12:31.000 --> 12:33.000
So one of the most effective strategies that it uses

12:33.000 --> 12:35.000
is if you look historically,

12:35.000 --> 12:38.000
if you look at cultural groups as sort of like nodal clouds

12:38.000 --> 12:40.000
that sort of overlap with each other,

12:40.000 --> 12:43.000
when you had a corrupted node within a nodal cloud

12:43.000 --> 12:45.000
or a node that looked like it was flipping,

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
what you would do if you were a majority Protestant country

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
or majority Catholic country and like a Catholic came in

12:49.000 --> 12:51.000
and started preaching or a Protestant came in and started preaching,

12:51.000 --> 12:52.000
you'd burn them.

12:52.000 --> 12:54.000
You'd burn them at the stake often, right?

12:54.000 --> 12:58.000
Or if somebody just had like random cultural mutation

12:58.000 --> 13:00.000
in the same way you have like random genetic mutation

13:00.000 --> 13:02.000
and they believe something weird like they were a witch

13:02.000 --> 13:03.000
and you burn them, right?

13:03.000 --> 13:06.000
That's how you maintain this level of cultural fidelity.

13:06.000 --> 13:09.000
What the virus does, which is very interesting,

13:09.000 --> 13:15.000
is it organically determines when a node looks like it might be flipping

13:15.000 --> 13:18.000
and then it essentially shadow bands the node.

13:18.000 --> 13:22.000
It begins to de-connect that node's links

13:22.000 --> 13:25.000
to all of the rest of the network's power structures.

13:25.000 --> 13:28.000
And this is really powerful because what it means

13:28.000 --> 13:31.000
is the other nodes that might be allied with that node,

13:31.000 --> 13:34.000
they don't react the way they would have historically

13:34.000 --> 13:36.000
when somebody was being like burned at the stake or something like that,

13:36.000 --> 13:39.000
which is actually why cancellation is a fairly ineffective tactic

13:39.000 --> 13:41.000
and genuinely not use that much

13:41.000 --> 13:44.000
when contrasted with just a shadow banding process

13:44.000 --> 13:46.000
of the person just doesn't get a promotion

13:46.000 --> 13:48.000
if it looks like they might be immune to these ideas.

13:48.000 --> 13:52.000
They just don't, you know, their papers get published a little less.

13:52.000 --> 13:56.000
You know, certain platforms begin to favor them less

13:56.000 --> 13:57.000
because of the algorithm.

13:57.000 --> 14:02.000
And that's how it has been able to maintain such control,

14:02.000 --> 14:05.000
I think, of the upper echelons of our society.

14:05.000 --> 14:10.000
But it's not like every organization is run by a progressive movement, right?

14:10.000 --> 14:14.000
There are organizations out there that seem to be a lot more open to new ideas.

14:14.000 --> 14:17.000
We're seeing pushback from a variety of places to the opportunity

14:17.000 --> 14:20.000
for people to have independent jobs.

14:20.000 --> 14:23.000
So I would say that it's not every organization.

14:23.000 --> 14:27.000
So it specifically targets the organizations it can best use

14:27.000 --> 14:30.000
to maintain its population levels.

14:30.000 --> 14:34.000
And so those are typically organizations that are involved in education.

14:34.000 --> 14:36.000
So you're looking at the middle school system,

14:36.000 --> 14:38.000
the high school system and the college system

14:38.000 --> 14:41.000
or the organization that it is most critical that it maintains

14:41.000 --> 14:43.000
an absolute strangleholdover.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
And this again comes to fertility issues.

14:45.000 --> 14:47.000
Of the populations of the world,

14:47.000 --> 14:50.000
if there is one population that has a very low birth rate,

14:50.000 --> 14:53.000
it is this population, this urban monoculture.

14:53.000 --> 15:00.000
And because of that, the only way it can repopulate its ideological faction

15:00.000 --> 15:05.000
is through siphoning children from other often more conservative cultural traditions

15:05.000 --> 15:07.000
or in other ways, deviant cultural traditions

15:07.000 --> 15:10.000
that are for whatever reason, having a lot of kids.

15:10.000 --> 15:13.000
Okay, getting back to fertility,

15:13.000 --> 15:18.000
what groups are doing particularly well and particularly badly when it comes to fertility?

15:18.000 --> 15:20.000
This is a fascinating question.

15:20.000 --> 15:25.000
All right, so if you look in a post-prosperity environment,

15:25.000 --> 15:26.000
so a lot of people, they're like,

15:26.000 --> 15:29.000
oh, well, countries in Africa are doing really well.

15:29.000 --> 15:33.000
They have high fertility rates or Muslim populations have high fertility rates.

15:33.000 --> 15:35.000
And it's like, well, that's irrelevant of those populations

15:35.000 --> 15:38.000
or in a country where the average salary is under $5,000 a year,

15:38.000 --> 15:40.000
because that is where you get above replacement fertility

15:40.000 --> 15:44.000
in pretty much every country that's under $5,000 a year, you get above replacement.

15:44.000 --> 15:48.000
Every country above $5,000 a year, you typically get below replacement fertility.

15:48.000 --> 15:51.000
And so it's a level of desperate poverty, first of all,

15:51.000 --> 15:52.000
that is often misconstrued.

15:52.000 --> 15:55.000
So you look at Latin America, Central America, South America, the Caribbean,

15:55.000 --> 16:00.000
collectively as of 2019, so old news, they fell below repopulation rate.

16:00.000 --> 16:03.000
So it's really just a few of these poorest countries.

16:03.000 --> 16:08.000
So I really ignore any country at a high fertility if it's a poor country

16:08.000 --> 16:10.000
or if it's not a wealthy country, right?

16:10.000 --> 16:14.000
